{"amendments":[{"body":"src/contexts/workflow_composition/retry_policy.rs:122-142 applies jitter after `delay.min(self.backoff_cap)`. That lets `backoff_for_attempt()` exceed the configured cap: with the default settings, attempt 5 is capped to 60s and then multiplied by up to 1.25, so the engine can sleep for roughly 75s even though `DEFAULT_BACKOFF_CAP_SECS` at lines 32-33 is documented as the maximum. Re-cap after jitter, or apply jitter before the final `min()`.","rationale":"This breaks the stated upper bound for retry delays and can make rate-limit recovery noticeably slower than intended."},{"body":"src/adapters/process_backend.rs:526-553 and 997-1008 misclassify some real missing-binary failures. In ambient-PATH mode `resolve_binary()` returns a bare name like `claude`, but the new spawn error path uses `!binary.exists()` to decide whether ENOENT should be `BinaryNotFound`. `Path::exists()` on a bare name checks the current working directory, not PATH, so an unrelated `./claude` or `./codex` file in the repo can turn a true PATH miss into `TransportFailure` and consume the full retry budget instead of failing terminally.","rationale":"This undermines the new non-retryable `BinaryNotFound` behavior for an unrecoverable setup error and can waste all retries before surfacing the actual problem."}],"summary":"Reviewed the retry-policy/process-backend/tmux changes and ran targeted tests (`cargo test retry_policy`, `cargo test process_backend_test::`, `cargo test tmux_adapter_test::`). The tests pass, but I found two correctness issues in the new backoff and spawn-error classification logic."}